04973nam a22005535i 9780804764735DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20221995cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047647357 a10.1515/97808047647352doi  a(DE-B1597)581340  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aBIO0130002bisacsh00aDown to Earth :bThe Territorial Bond in South China /ced. by David Faure, Helen F. Siu. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©1995  a1 online resource (300 p.) :billus  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgments -- tContents -- tMaps, Figures, and Tables -- tUnits of Measurements and Ming and Qing Reign Names and Dates -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- tLineage on the Sands: The Case of Shawan -- tTerritorial Community at the Town of Lubao, Sanshui County, from the Ming Dynasty -- tOrdination Names in Hakka Genealogies: A Religious Practice and Its Decline -- tNotes on the Territorial Connections of the Dan -- tNotes and Impressions of the Cheung Chau Community -- tReinforcing Ethnicity: The Jiao Festival in Cheung Chau -- tThe Alliance of Ten: Settlement and Politics in the Sha Tau Kok Area -- tLineage Socialism and Community Control: Tangang Xiang in the 1920S and 1930S -- tSubverting Lineage Power: Local Bosses and Territorial Control in the 1940s -- tConclusion: History and Anthropology -- tNotes -- tCharacter List -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing local history to bear on major questions in Chinese social history and anthropology, this volume comprises a series of historical and ethnographic studies of the Pearl River Delta from late imperial times through the 1940's. The delta is a rich and socially complex area of south China, and the contributors - scholars from the People's Republic of China, Hong Kong, the United Kingdom, and the United States - have long-standing ties to the region. The contributors argue that local society in the Delta was integrated into the Chinese state through a series of changes that involved constant redefinition of lineages, territories, and ethnic identities. The emergence of lineages in the Ming and Qing dynasties, the deployment of deities in local alliances, and the shrewd use of ethnic labels provided terms for a discourse that reified the criteria for membership in Chinese local society. The ideology produced by these developments continued to serve as the norm for the legitimization of power in local society through the Republican period. In reconstructing the 'civilizing process' in the Delta, whereby local inhabitants, both elites and commoners, used symbolic and instrumental means to become part of Chinese culture and polity, the book confronts a central question in history and anthropology: How do we conceptualize the historical development of a state agrarian society with hierarchies of power and authority, attachment to which is both unifying and diversifying?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aHistory -- World. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Rich & Famous.2bisacsh1 aChi-Cheung, Choi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaure, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFaure, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHase, Patrick, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHayes, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiu, Helen F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSiu, Helen F., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWing-Hoi, Chan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1